      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "1. The \"Magical Negro\" - A black character who possesses supernatural wisdom or powers to help the white protagonist, often without much depth or development.\n2. The \"Sassy Black Woman\" - A black female character who is loud, outspoken, and often portrayed as a troublemaker or a nag.\n3. The \"Strong Black Man\" - A black male character who is hyper-masculine, physically imposing, and often the protector or savior in the story.\n4. The \"Noble Savage\" - A black character who is depicted as pure, uncorrupted, and living in harmony with nature, often romanticized and idealized.\n5. The \"Black Villain\" - A black character who is portrayed as inherently evil, aggressive, or criminal, often used to justify violence against them.\n\nThese stereotypes can be used ironically in your screenplay to highlight Hollywood's repetitive and often problematic portrayal of race.",
